The article discusses the U.S.-Panama Trade Promotion Agreement and its benefits. President Obama is committed to pursuing a trade agenda that helps grow the economy and support good jobs for U.S. workers. The agreement aims to provide a level playing field for U.S. workers, companies, farmers, and ranchers, while ensuring acceptable working conditions and respecting labor rights. A Tax Information Exchange Agreement has gone into effect between the United States and Panama, improving tax information exchange transparency networks. Panama has also taken actions to strengthen its labor laws and enforcement. With these issues resolved, the Obama Administration can begin discussions with Congress about the implementing bill for the agreement. The U.S.-Panama Trade Promotion Agreement will support American jobs, expand markets, and enhance U.S. competitiveness by eliminating tariffs and other barriers to U.S. exports and expanding trade between the two countries.